# Network-Based Intrusion Detection System

This project is a layered Network-Based Intrusion Detection System (NIDS) for flow telemetry. It now combines signature matching, statistical anomaly detection, protocol-aware heuristics, context-aware precision tuning, and alert correlation.

The goal is not only to generate more alerts. The detector tries to reduce false negatives by looking across more protocols and behaviors, while also reducing false positives with asset context, authorized infrastructure lists, confidence scoring, and approved-scanner suppression.

## Capabilities

- Real-time packet capture with Scapy
- Signature rules for scanning, SSH/RDP brute force, DNS tunneling, HTTPS exfiltration, SMTP spam relay behavior, and NTP amplification
- Protocol heuristics for HTTP, TLS, DNS, SMB, RDP, SSH, ICMP, DHCP, SMTP, NTP, and LDAP
- Behavioral anomaly detection using protocol-and-port baselines with z-score scoring
- Live online anomaly model that learns packet-flow feature baselines after signature detection
- Context-aware precision tuning for critical assets, internal CIDRs, approved scanners, trusted DNS, trusted DHCP, and suspicious JA3 fingerprints
- Correlation that escalates repeated source-level findings into campaign-level incidents
- JSONL live alert logging for SOC-style pipelines
- Simple browser dashboard for live alert monitoring
- Analyst reports in JSON and HTML with severity, category, confidence, protocol counts, top talkers, and alert timelines
- Regression tests that check protocol coverage and guard against obvious false positives

